        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The correlator is mostly setup for continuum observations with one baseband reserved for serendipitous CO line detection. The spectral channel width is appropriate for gas emission in a protoplanetary disk.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>0.031 arcsecond resolution is required to resolve the disk cavity and to locate precisely the disk edge. 400 milliarcseconds is comprable to the estimated disk size from Andrews et al. (2011). There are no reports of any significant millimeter emission from HD98800 A, ~ 1 arcsecond away, so we do not believe it merits consideration in the largest angular scale calculation.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>To test dynamical theories of disk truncation, we require the ability to locate the disk edge to well within a synthesized beam. Figure 1 in the science justification shows the likelihood function for the truncation radius (in milliarcseconds), showing that a range of a few milliarcseconds is within the reasonable limits for this predicted quantity. We propose to locate the disk edge to within 0.5 milliarcseconds.

To estimate the sensitivity required for this observation, we take the 345 GHz flux from Andrews et al., 2011 (110 mJy) and extrapolate it to 230 GHz, using a nu^3 power law, a reasonable choice if grains in the disk are ~ mm-sized.   We then assume an intrinsic r^-1 power-law for the emissivity of the disk as a function of radius, from an inner radius of ~ 43 milliarcsec (see Fig. 1) to an outer radius corresponding to the disk radius estimate from Andrews et al., ~ 300 milliarcsec. This gives an estimated peak flux density at the inner disk edge of ~ 2 mJy/beam. Locating the disk edge to within 0.5 milliarcsec requires a SNR of 60 at the disk edge (relative astrometric accuracy is the resolution of the telescope / SNR). Thus we require 2 mJy/ 60 = 33 uJy sensitivity to properly locate the disk edge. 

The CO setup is to attempt to detect any gas serendipitously. There have been no detections of CO in the system, but if there is gas in this disk, it is likely to play a role in the grain dynamics, so we wish to constrain it using low-resolution observations.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
