        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The correlator is mostly setup for continuum observations with one baseband reserved for serendipitous CO line detection. The spectral channel width is appropriate for gas emission in a protoplanetary disk.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The disk extent of HD98800 is ~ 0.3-0.5 arcseconds, and the simulation in Fig. 2 of the science justification shows that with a reasonable model of the disk structure, ~ 30-40 % of the disk flux is not recovered in the longest configuration due to the lack of short spacings. We require overlapping baselines to ensure consisent cross-calibration, so our requested angular resolution is slightly less than the largest angular scale available in the longer baseline configuration. The requested largest angular scale here is motivated by the disk extent in HD 98800 B. </prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The sensitivity chosen here is sufficient to provide short-spacing data that overlaps with the requested long-baseline data and not completely dominate the MCMC fitting, provided that the weather for each observation is comparable. It is impossible to go to lower sensitivities due to timing (time on source must be greater than 2 minutes).

The CO setup is to attempt to detect any gas serendipitously. There have been no detections of CO in the system, but if there is gas in this disk, it is likely to play a role in the grain dynamics, so we wish to constrain it using low-resolution observations.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
