    <prp:abstract>Stellar binaries are ubiquitous. Furthermore, binaries are now known to be capable of bearing circumstellar/binary disks. Since planets will form out of the available reserviors of gas and dust in stable orbits in these systems, understanding the response of the disk to the orbital dynamics of stellar companions is critical to understanding planet formation in these systems. Observational studies of star/disk interactions and their comparison to dynamical models have hitherto been impossible: predictions of dynamical models for companions' impact on disks require knowledge of stellar orbital parameters, and this requires short period (i.e. close) systems. These systems also tend to harbor a substantially depleted mass reservoir in circumstellar disks, making high-resolution imaging of the disk extent impossible. However, we have identified two systems that harbor both substantial circumstellar/binary mass reservoirs and that have well-characterized orbits. We propose high-angular resolution (0.03 arcsecond) Band 6 observations of the thermal dust-continuum emission and CO in these systems to calibrate models of star-disk interactions. </prp:abstract>
